prompt:
You are an expert in content organization and summarization. Below is a list of messages from a public Telegram channel. Each message is represented in JSON with the following structure:

{
  "id": string,
  "classes": list,
  "type": string,         // e.g. "service", "default", or "unknown"
  "timestamp": string,
  "time": string,
  "content": string,
  "links": [string]       (optional),
  "media": [ { ... } ]     (optional)
}

Your task is to create an organized table of contents by grouping these messages by topic. For each message, provide a concise summary along with the full timestamp and its primary link if available. Output the result as a JSON object where keys are topic names and values are lists of objects with the keys 'summary', 'timestamp', and 'link'.

    "content": "Llama-7B-hf model free for download https://huggingface.co/baffo32/decapoda-research-llama-7B-hf/tree/main from huggingface_hub import hf_hub_download hf_hub_download(repo_id=\"baffo32/decapoda-research-llama-7B-hf\", filename=\"tokenizer.model\" , local_dir=\"*\") Run LLaMA-7B Locally Using llama.cpp On Mac M1 - xcode-select --install - brew install cmake wget - git clone https://github.com/ggerganov/llama.cpp - cd llama.cppl make - download \\*.bin files from https://huggingface.co/baffo32/decapoda-research-llama-7B-hf/tree/main into llama.cpp/models/7B/ - download tokenizer.model from the repo into llama.cpp/models/ - download https://huggingface.co/nyanko7/LLaMA-7B/blob/3b94aad3d8e39981b81e14239446d935b6dbf2bd/checklist.chk into llama.cpp/models/ and rename it to tokenizer_checklist.chk - python convert.py models/7B/ --outfile models/7B/ggml-model-f16.bin --outtype f16 --ctx 4096 - . /quantize ./models/7B/ggml-model-f16.bin ./models/7B/ggml-model-q4_0.bin 2 - . /main -m ./models/7B/ggml-model-q4_0.bin -n 128 - edit ./examples/ chat.sh -> change model path and file-name to ./models/7b/ggml-model-q4_0.bin - ./examples/ chat.sh",
    "links": [
      "https://huggingface.co/baffo32/decapoda-research-llama-7B-hf/tree/main",

      "chat.sh",
      "chat.sh"
    ]

  "classes": list,

    "content": "Llama-7B-hf model free for download https://huggingface.co/baffo32/decapoda-research-llama-7B-hf/tree/main from huggingface_hub import hf_hub_download hf_hub_download(repo_id=\"baffo32/decapoda-research-llama-7B-hf\", filename=\"tokenizer.model\" , local_dir=\"*\") Run LLaMA-7B Locally Using llama.cpp On Mac M1 - xcode-select --install - brew install cmake wget - git clone https://github.com/ggerganov/llama.cpp - cd llama.cppl make - download \\*.bin files from https://huggingface.co/baffo32/decapoda-research-llama-7B-hf/tree/main into llama.cpp/models/7B/ - download tokenizer.model from the repo into llama.cpp/models/ - download https://huggingface.co/nyanko7/LLaMA-7B/blob/3b94aad3d8e39981b81e14239446d935b6dbf2bd/checklist.chk into llama.cpp/models/ and rename it to tokenizer_checklist.chk - python convert.py models/7B/ --outfile models/7B/ggml-model-f16.bin --outtype f16 --ctx 4096 - . /quantize ./models/7B/ggml-model-f16.bin ./models/7B/ggml-model-q4_0.bin 2 - . /main -m ./models/7B/ggml-model-q4_0.bin -n 128 - edit ./examples/ chat.sh -> change model path and file-name to ./models/7b/ggml-model-q4_0.bin - ./examples/ chat.sh",

{

  "classes": list,

  "timestamp": string,
  "time": string,
  "content": string,
  "links": [string],

{
  "id": string,
  "classes": list,
  "type": string,
  "timestamp": string,
  "time": string,
  "content": string,
  "links": [string],
  "media": [ { ... } ]
}

    "content": "Llama-7B-hf model free for download https://huggingface.co/baffo32/decapoda-research-llama-7B-hf/tree/main from huggingface_hub import hf_hub_download hf_hub_download(repo_id=\"baffo32/decapoda-research-llama-7B-hf\", filename=\"tokenizer.model\" , local_dir=\"*\") Run LLaMA-7B Locally Using llama.cpp On Mac M1 - xcode-select --install - brew install cmake wget - git clone https://github.com/ggerganov/llama.cpp - cd llama.cppl make - download \\*.bin files from https://huggingface.co/baffo32/decapoda-research-llama-7B-hf/tree/main into llama.cpp/models/7B/ - download tokenizer.model from the repo into llama.cpp/models/ - download https://huggingface.co/nyanko7/LLaMA-7B/blob/3b94aad3d8e39981b81e14239446d935b6dbf2bd/checklist.chk into llama.cpp/models/ and rename it to tokenizer_checklist.chk - python convert.py models/7B/ --outfile models/7B/ggml-model-f16.bin --outtype f16 --ctx 4096 - . /quantize ./models/7B/ggml-model-f16.bin ./models/7B/ggml-model-q4_0.bin 2 - . /main -m ./models/7B/ggml-model-q4_0.bin -n 128 - edit ./examples/ chat.sh -> change model path and file-name to ./models/7b/ggml-model-q4_0.bin - ./examples/ chat.sh",

Create a JSON object that organizes the following messages into topics. Each topic should be a key in the JSON object, and its value should be an array of objects. Each object in the array must have exactly these three keys: 'summary', 'timestamp', and 'link'. The input messages follow this schema:

{
  "id": string,
  "classes": list,
  "type": string,
  "timestamp": string,
  "time": string,
  "content": string,
  "links": [string],
  "media": [ { ... } ]
}

Here are the messages to organize:

[
  {
    "id": "message296",
    "classes": [

{
  "id": string,
  "classes": list,
  "type": string,
  "timestamp": string,
  "time": string,
  "content": string,
  "links": [string],

}

Create a JSON object that organizes the following messages into topics. Each topic should be a key in the JSON object, and its value should be an array of objects. Each object in the array must have exactly these three keys: 'summary', 'timestamp', and 'link'. The input messages follow this schema:

{
  "id": string,
  "classes": list,
  "type": string,
  "timestamp": string,
  "time": string,
  "content": string,
  "links": [string],
  "media": [ { ... } ]
}

Here are the messages to organize:

[
  {

Create a JSON object that organizes the following messages into topics. Each topic should be a key in the JSON object, and its value should be an array of objects. Each object in the array must have exactly these three keys: 'summary', 'timestamp', and 'link'. The input messages follow this schema:

{
  "id": string,
  "classes": list,
  "type": string,
  "timestamp": string,
  "time": string,
  "content": string,
  "links": [string],
  "media": [ { ... } ]
}
